</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-67_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-68_ pf-text-1"><strong>Compliance with legislation and regulations</strong> - Healthcare providers must adhere to various laws and regulations to ensure high standards of care. Key legislation includes the Health and Social Care Act 2012, the Care Act 2014, and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR). Compliance involves regular audits, staff training, and robust policies and procedures.


</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-70_ pf-text-1"><strong>Staff training and development</strong> - Investing in staff training is essential for maintaining compliance and improving patient care. Regular training programmes on topics such as safeguarding, infection control, and data protection help ensure that staff are knowledgeable and competent.

